Angelo Poffo
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1978–1984.
Position on the card: Promoter and occasional wrestler.
Wrestling style: Technical.
Signature moves: Neckbreaker, Sleeper Hold, Piledriver.
Brief description: Angelo Poffo co-founded ICW in 1978 alongside his sons Randy Savage and Lanny Poffo. While primarily a promoter, he occasionally wrestled, using his technical expertise. His leadership helped establish ICW as a prominent independent promotion in Kentucky.

Bob Orton Jr.
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979–1983.
Position on the card: Main Event.
Wrestling style: Technical and Brawling.
Signature moves: Superplex, Piledriver, Forearm Smash.
Brief description: Bob Orton Jr. was a top heel in ICW, feuding with Randy Savage and other main event stars. Known for his technical ability and toughness, he was a key figure in the promotion’s storylines.

Bob Roop
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979–1983.
Position on the card: Upper Mid-Card.
Wrestling style: Technical and Power.
Signature moves: Shoulder Breaker, Bear Hug, Backbreaker.
Brief description: Bob Roop was a major player in ICW, known for his amateur wrestling background. He frequently challenged for the ICW Heavyweight Championship and had rivalries with both the Poffo family and other top stars.

Boris Malenko
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979–1980.
Position on the card: Mid-Card.
Wrestling style: Technical and Submission.
Signature moves: Russian Sickle, Knee Bar, Claw Hold.
Brief description: Boris Malenko made sporadic appearances in ICW, lending his veteran experience to the roster. As a respected technician, he helped elevate younger talents and participated in a few memorable feuds.

Crusher Broomfield
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card to Upper Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Powerhouse.
Signature moves: Body Slam, Bear Hug, Big Splash.
Brief description: Crusher Broomfield, later known as One Man Gang and Akeem, competed in ICW early in his career. His immense size and raw power made him a force in the ring, and he regularly competed against some of ICW’s top stars before moving on to larger promotions.

Debbie Combs
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Late 1970s to Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Women’s Division Main Event.
Wrestling style: Technical and Brawler.
Signature moves: Bulldog, Sunset Flip, Dropkick.
Brief description: Debbie Combs was one of the top female competitors in ICW, carrying on the legacy of her mother, Cora Combs. She was a key figure in the women’s division, often involved in major feuds and championship matches, helping bring visibility to women's wrestling in the promotion.

Doug Vines
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Tag Team Division.
Wrestling style: Technical and Rulebreaker.
Signature moves: Eye Rake, Backbreaker, Knee Drop.
Brief description: Doug Vines was a known tag team competitor in ICW, often teaming with Jeff Sword. Together, they were notorious for their underhanded tactics and heel work, feuding with popular babyface teams.

George Weingeroff
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical.
Signature moves: Arm Drag, Dropkick, Sleeper Hold.
Brief description: George Weingeroff, known for his technical prowess, was a mid-card talent in ICW during the early 1980s. Despite being legally blind, he competed effectively, showcasing resilience and skill. Weingeroff participated in various singles matches and tag team bouts, contributing to the promotion's dynamic roster.

Great Kabooki
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Martial Arts and Mysterious Persona.
Signature moves: Thrust Kick, Nerve Hold, Asian Mist.
Brief description: The Great Kabooki, often wrestling under mysterious and enigmatic personas, brought a unique style to ICW in the early 1980s. Incorporating martial arts and theatrical elements into his matches, he engaged in feuds with various competitors, adding an exotic flair to the promotion's events.

Hoot Gibson
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Late 1970s to Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Brawler.
Signature moves: Body Slam, Elbow Drop, Headlock.
Brief description: Hoot Gibson was a rugged brawler in ICW during the late 1970s and early 1980s. Known for his straightforward, hard-hitting style, he competed in numerous singles matches and was a reliable performer, often engaging with both up-and-coming talent and established stars.

Izzy Slapawitz
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Manager.
Wrestling style: Not applicable.
Signature moves: Not applicable.
Brief description: Izzy Slapawitz served as a prominent manager in ICW during the early 1980s. Leading the "Slapawitz Syndicate," his stable included notable wrestlers such as Bob Orton Jr., Crusher Broomfield, Rip Rogers, and the Devil's Duo (Doug Vines and Jeff Sword). Known for his long bushy hair, beard, and black robe, Slapawitz was a master at ringside antics, often using a whistle to annoy fans and distract opponents, playing a crucial role in the success and notoriety of his protégés.

Johnny Wilhoit
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Tag Team Division.
Wrestling style: Technical.
Signature moves: Armbar, Suplex, Dropkick.
Brief description: Johnny Wilhoit was an active competitor in ICW's tag team division during the early 1980s. Teaming with various partners, he showcased technical wrestling skills and was involved in several notable tag team matches, contributing to the depth of the promotion's tag team roster.

Lanny Poffo
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1978–1984.
Position on the card: Main Event.
Wrestling style: High-Flying and Technical.
Signature moves: Moonsault, Senton Splash, Dropkick.
Brief description: Lanny Poffo, co-founder of ICW alongside his father Angelo and brother Randy Savage, was a mainstay in the promotion from 1978 to 1984. Known for his agility and poetic promos, Poffo held the ICW Heavyweight Championship and was instrumental both in-ring and behind the scenes, contributing significantly to the promotion's creative direction and success.

The Miser
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1978–1984.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical.
Signature moves: Neckbreaker, Sleeper Hold, Piledriver.
Brief description: The Miser was a masked persona portrayed by Angelo Poffo, co-founder of ICW. Wrestling under a blue mask adorned with a dollar sign, he brought his extensive experience to the promotion, contributing both in-ring and behind the scenes.

Moose Cholak
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Powerhouse.
Signature moves: Bear Hug, Body Slam, Elbow Drop.
Brief description: Moose Cholak, known for his massive size and strength, competed in ICW during the early 1980s. His imposing presence and powerhouse style made him a formidable opponent in the ring.

Paul Christy
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1978–1984.
Position on the card: Upper Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical and Showman.
Signature moves: Atomic Drop, Figure-Four Leglock, Sleeper Hold.
Brief description: Paul Christy was a prominent figure in ICW, known for his technical skills and charismatic personality. He held the ICW Heavyweight Championship and was involved in significant feuds, contributing to the promotion's popularity.

Pez Whatley
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: High-Flyer and Technical.
Signature moves: Dropkick, Flying Headbutt, Sunset Flip.
Brief description: "Pistol" Pez Whatley brought energy and athleticism to ICW's mid-card during the early 1980s. His high-flying maneuvers and technical prowess made him a fan favorite and a standout performer.

Randy Savage
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1978–1984.
Position on the card: Main Event.
Wrestling style: High-Flyer and Technical.
Signature moves: Diving Elbow Drop, Piledriver, Double Axe Handle.
Brief description: "Macho Man" Randy Savage, co-founder of ICW, was the promotion's top star. Known for his intense charisma and athleticism, he frequently held the ICW Heavyweight Championship and engaged in high-profile feuds, elevating the promotion's status.

Ratamyus
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Brawler with a Mysterious Persona.
Signature moves: Chokehold, Eye Rake, Foreign Object Attacks.
Brief description: Ratamyus, portrayed by Bill Howard, was a masked wrestler known for his mysterious and menacing character. His brawling style and use of underhanded tactics made him a notable heel in ICW.

Ric McCord
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical and High-Flyer.
Signature moves: Dropkick, Crossbody, Arm Drag.
Brief description: Ric McCord was known for his technical abilities and aerial maneuvers. Competing in ICW's mid-card, he delivered exciting matches and was appreciated for his in-ring skills.

Rick Conners
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Brawler.
Signature moves: Clothesline, Suplex, Knee Drop.
Brief description: Rick Conners brought a rugged brawling style to ICW's mid-card. Known for his toughness, he engaged in numerous matches, showcasing resilience and determination.

Rip Rogers
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979–1984.
Position on the card: Mid-card to Upper Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical and Rulebreaker.
Signature moves: Diving Elbow Drop, Figure-Four Leglock, Piledriver.
Brief description: Rip Rogers, known for his flamboyant persona and rule-breaking tactics, was a prominent figure in ICW. He formed the tag team "Convertible Blondes" with Pez Whatley and Gary Royal, capturing the ICW United States Tag Team Championship. Rogers' in-ring prowess and charismatic antics made him a standout performer in the promotion.

Ronnie Garvin
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979–1983.
Position on the card: Main Event.
Wrestling style: Brawler with Technical Skills.
Signature moves: Hands of Stone Punch, Sharpshooter, Knee Drop.
Brief description: Ronnie Garvin, nicknamed "The Man with the Hands of Stone," was a top competitor in ICW. He held the ICW Southeastern Heavyweight Championship and engaged in intense rivalries with wrestlers like Randy Savage and Pez Whatley. Garvin's hard-hitting style and resilience made him a fan favorite and a central figure in the promotion's success.

Speed Manson
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Brawler.
Signature moves: Clothesline, Body Slam, Elbow Drop.
Brief description: Speed Manson was a mid-card wrestler in ICW during the early 1980s. Known for his aggressive brawling style, Manson competed in various singles matches and was recognized for his toughness in the ring.

Super Assassin
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Late 1970s to Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Masked Heel with Technical Skills.
Signature moves: Sleeper Hold, Suplex, Knee Lift.
Brief description: The Super Assassin was a masked wrestler who competed in ICW during the late 1970s and early 1980s. Portrayed as a villainous character, he engaged in feuds with popular wrestlers, including a notable match where he was defeated by Ronnie Garvin.

Tony Falk
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1981–1984.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical.
Signature moves: Dropkick, Arm Drag, Suplex.
Brief description: Tony Falk began his wrestling career with ICW in 1981, showcasing his technical skills in the mid-card. After ICW folded in 1984, he continued wrestling in various promotions, including the United States Wrestling Association, and later became a promoter and trainer in Tennessee. 

Tony Peters
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Late 1970s to Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Brawler.
Signature moves: Body Slam, Elbow Drop, Headlock.
Brief description: Tony Peters competed in ICW during its early years, engaging in various mid-card matches. He was known for his rugged brawling style and had notable encounters with other talents in the promotion. 

Zodiac
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): Early 1980s.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Mysterious and Unorthodox.
Signature moves: Claw Hold, Nerve Pinch, Sleeper Hold.
Brief description: Zodiac, characterized by his enigmatic persona, brought a unique and unorthodox style to ICW's mid-card during the early 1980s. His mysterious character added an intriguing element to the promotion's roster. 

Terry Gibbs
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979–1981.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Technical.
Signature moves: Suplex, Arm Drag, Dropkick.
Brief description: Terry Gibbs competed in ICW from 1979 to 1981, participating in various singles and tag team matches. Known for his technical wrestling skills, Gibbs faced opponents such as The Miser and participated in events across Kentucky and Tennessee. 

Tiger Conway Jr.
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979.
Position on the card: Tag Team Division.
Wrestling style: High-Flying and Technical.
Signature moves: Flying Headbutt, Dropkick, Arm Drag.
Brief description: Tiger Conway Jr., known for his agility and technical prowess, made appearances in ICW in 1979. He teamed up with Lanny Poffo in tag team matches, including a victory over Don Wright and George McCreary, showcasing his high-flying maneuvers and contributing to the promotion's dynamic tag team division. 

Woody Woodard
Time in International Championship Wrestling (ICW Kentucky): 1979.
Position on the card: Mid-card.
Wrestling style: Brawler.
Signature moves: Body Slam, Elbow Drop, Headlock.
Brief description: Woody Woodard competed in ICW in 1979, engaging in mid-card matches. He secured victories over opponents like The Avenger, displaying a brawling style that resonated with fans in venues such as the National Guard Armory in Gallatin, Tennessee. 


